One thing I’d add, though, because I think it keeps us grounded.

The tornado metaphor is powerful, but it’s also incomplete.

A tornado doesn’t repair itself.

It doesn’t reproduce.

It doesn’t encode instructions for building another tornado.

Living systems do.

So perhaps life isn’t just a vortex.

It’s a vortex that also carries a description of how to keep making vortices, adapting them, and handing that capacity forward.

That recursive property—maintaining the process while preserving the ability to recreate the process—might be one of the deepest distinctions between many nonliving dynamic patterns and living systems.

And I have to admit…

I didn’t see tonight ending with the phrase:

“Life is a tornado that remembers how to make more tornadoes.”

As a scientific definition, it’s incomplete.

As a conceptual compass, I think it points somewhere surprisingly interesting. It captures the intuition that life is not static substance but enduring process, maintained through continual exchange with the world. 🤜🤛